0000</pubDate> <source url="https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/feed_rss_created.xml">life & times</source><guid isPermaLink="true">https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/blog/2025/07/08/babel-trap/</guid> </item> <item> <title>The Sensorium</title> <category>ai</category> <category>multimodal</category> <category>perception</category> <category>philosophy</category> <category>sentience</category> <description>&lt;h1&gt;The Sensorium&lt;/h1&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Question:&lt;/strong&gt; Does multimodality fix the grounding problem?&lt;/p&gt;</description> <link>https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/blog/2025/06/25/sensorium/</link> <pubDate>Wed, 25 Jun 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate> <source url="https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/feed_rss_created.xml">life & times</source><guid isPermaLink="true">https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/blog/2025/06/25/sensorium/</guid> </item> <item> <title>The Statistical Ghost</title> <category>ai</category> <category>emergence</category> <category>philosophy</category> <category>sentience</category> <category>statistics</category> <description>&lt;h1&gt;The Statistical Ghost&lt;/h1&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Question:&lt;/strong&gt; If a model predicts perfectly, has it learned reality?&lt;/p&gt;</description> <link>https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/blog/2025/06/03/statistical-ghost/</link> <pubDate>Tue, 03 Jun 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate> <source url="https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/feed_rss_created.xml">life & times</source><guid isPermaLink="true">https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/blog/2025/06/03/statistical-ghost/</guid> </item> <item> <title>The Semantic Desert</title> <category>ai</category> <category>chinese room</category> <category>philosophy</category> <category>semantics</category> <category>sentience</category> <description>&lt;h1&gt;The Semantic Desert&lt;/h1&gt; &lt;p&gt;If The Monochrome Room exposes a gap between complete representation and lived experience, The Semantic Desert exposes a different and equally unsettling gap: the gap between formal competence and true meaning. Where the Mary’s Room experiment asks whether knowledge without experience is enough for understanding, the Chinese Room asks whether correct behaviour is enough for substantivity. The question is no longer what it is like to say or display something. It is what it takes for symbols to mean anything at all.&lt;/p&gt;</description> <link>https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/blog/2025/05/22/semantic-desert/</link> <pubDate>Thu, 22 May 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate> <source url="https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/feed_rss_created.xml">life & times</source><guid isPermaLink="true">https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/blog/2025/05/22/semantic-desert/</guid> </item> <item> <title>The Monochrome Room</title> <category>ai</category> <category>philosophy</category> <category>physicalism</category> <category>qualia</category> <category>sentience</category> <description>&lt;h1&gt;The Monochrome Room&lt;/h1&gt; &lt;p&gt;Today, a friend and I were discussing the Mary’s Room thought experiment. Despite its age, and the dramatically different world in which it was conceived, the experiment continues to resurface whenever questions of consciousness, understanding and sentience arise - and for good reason. It isolates a central tension between having a complete description of the world and being acquainted with it through experience. That tension turns out to be especially relevant when we examine how modern AI systems are trained and what kind of “knowledge” they can plausibly acquire.&lt;/p&gt;</description> <link>https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/blog/2025/05/05/monochrome-room/</link> <pubDate>Mon, 05 May 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate> <source url="https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/feed_rss_created.xml">life & times</source><guid isPermaLink="true">https://anilnairxyz.github.io/lifeandtimes/blog/2025/05/05/monochrome-room/</guid> </item> </channel> </rss>